Special Programming
Because of a need to conserve power on this system we have installed special programming.
If there is a QSO anywhere on the system that goes for 5 minutes without anyone transmitting directly on this repeater, it will unlink from the system.
It is still listening, so when the QSO on the system goes quiet for one minute it will relink to the system.

1) If someone in the QSO is transmitting directly on the RX of this repeater with the link PL, then it will stay linked into the rest of the system.
It will not unlink after 5 minutes.
2) If someone is in the coverage area and wants to bring the machine back into linked mode then just kerchunk it with the link PL.

The K0CNM repeater is operated by the Denison Repeater Association. The repeater first went online in 1970. In 2000, the current repeater was purchased from the Iowa Department of Transportation. The repeater was located at the Iowa State Patrol Tower on the west side of Denison, IA on IA-59 North, with an antenna located at 250 feet. The Iowa State Patrol was gracious enough to provide the tower space and a building to house the repeater for years. In 2011 the Denison Repeater was taken offline and moved to a temporary location at the home QTH of KD0E, as the Iowa Department of Safety needed more tower space for their own equipment as they upgraded. In November 2013, the repeater finally found itself a new home located on a public safety tower just north of Denison, IA with current antenna at 150 feet.

This 444.1000 MHz repeater was the first repeater in the W4WSM system, going ON-AIR circa 1986. Today, this repeater is operating as a mixed mode FM and P25 machine. The repeater is a Motorola Quantar. In FM mode, it uses standard wide FM mode (25 KHz) bandwidth requiring a 100 Hz Uplink Tone for access to open the repeater squelch. This repeater also transmits a 100 Hz tone. NOTE: When you set up your radio, please be sure to program this repeater with a100 Hz Downlink Tone so you will NOT have to hear the P25 digital signal noise (while you are listening for FM Analog voice signals) when P25 is being transmitted.

Stanley KLOCK Obituary KLOCK, Stanley W.
Mr. Stanley W. Klock, 73 died April 24, 2013, in Mesa, AZ. Mr. Klock was born in Manchester on Nov. 5, 1939. He lived in Manchester during his younger years then relocated to Cheshire, before moving to Warren, ME in the late 1980s and then to Mesa, AZ in the late 1990s. Stanley attended the University of Hartford receiving a Bachelor of Science degree in electrical engineering prior to being employed by the Bristol Company in Waterbury. Stanley, K1EHO, was very active in the ham radio community often volunteering in times of natural disasters. In recent years Stanley was very active in the Coast Guard Reserve assisting the Coast Guard with their homeland security efforts. Survivors include his wife of six years, Mary Klock; son's Dexter and Douglas and five grandchildren, Nathaniel, Shelby, Tanner, Sheridan and Dexter; and brother Peter Klock. Stanley was preceded in death by his son, Stanley Winfield Klock Jr. (Brothie) and his brother Stephen Klock.
A memorial service will be held at Holmes-Watkins Funeral Home, 400 Main St., Manchester, CT 06040, 860-643-2441 on May 12, 2013 at 2 p.m. Memorial contributions can be made to your local SPCA as Stanley was an avid dog lover.

Published by Hartford Courant on May 8, 2013.

The main repeaters that are used the most are county owned, but they operate under the NR3K Grand Canyon Repeater Group call sign. It is a voted, repeated simulcast system using the latest Motorola GTR 8000 commercial base stations on county owned towers connected by microwave and with full backup power. We have 3 repeaters on 147.06 and 4 repeaters on 147.195 spread around the county. They are normally linked by a console patch at 911 but they can be unlinked on request to operate independently. With these 7 towers all connected by simulcast, we have HT coverage for nearly everywhere in the county. On this simulcast system you can also dial 911 with no special symbols and a 911 dispatcher will answer directly on the repeater system. This is not a phone patch, it is in their console.  The NR3K club also has a standalone repeater on Cedar Mountain, which is the highest point in the county and is located in the southeast area of the county. This is the repeater that was used by the NWS office to talk to us. This is the 145.21 repeater and is also linked to 443.65 at the same site. One of our simulcast repeaters on 147.195 is located at the same site but a different tower.

TS1: Texas Statewide – TG3148 North America – TG3 (15min PTT) Worldwide English – TG1 (15min PTT) AMSAT – TG98006 (15min PTT)  TS2: North Texas Wide – TG8205 Local – TG9  The “15min PTT” means that you need to kerchunk the repeater to link it to this talkgroup. This tells the C-Bridge that someone is listening to this talkgroup, and the C-Bridge will then route it to the repeater.  The “Local” talkgroup, TG9, is not routed through the C-Bridge. TG9 on TS2 is a preferred way for locals to talk on a given a repeater and not have it routed to other repeaters. We would highly suggest you program this in your radio, as some features may be added to link it to the 147.12 repeater when the net mode is active (this will come at a later date)

In Full Auto . WIRES-X. Our Yaesu Fusion C4FM UHF repeater is linked to WIRES-X. The node number is 30372. Our WIRES-X connectivity allows an operator to link to any other WIRES-X node or room through the internet. This allows you with your HT or mobile station to communicate with people in other cities, states or indeed other countries. The default room that our Fusion node is connected to is the Texas–Nexus, which is a wide variety of repeaters around the state, that gets visitors from all around the world.
So long as the repeater is not in use, feel free to link it to other nodes or rooms, make contacts in other countries. The room list is available here. It will return to its default configuration after a period of inactivity. Or, feel free to join us through WIRES-X, room 30372.
